n     3→description: Triage E2E test failures — download CI artifacts, classify flaky vs real bug, create PRs for flaky fixes and GitHub issues for real bugs\\n     4→---\\n     5→\\n     6→# E2E Triage\\n     7→\\n     8→Automate triage of E2E test failures. Analyze artifacts, classify each failure as **flaky** (agent non-determinism) or **real-bug** (CLI defect), then take action: batched PR for flaky fixes, GitHub issues for real bugs.\\n     9→\\n    10→## Inputs\\n    11→\\n    12→The user provides one of:\\n    13→- **`latest`** — download artifacts from the most recent failed E2E run on main\\n    14→- **A run ID or URL** — download artifacts from that specific run\\n    15→- **A local path** — use existing artifact directory (skip download)\\n    16→\\n    17→## Step 1: Download Artifacts\\n    18→\\n    19→**If given a run ID, URL, or \\\"latest\\\":**\\n    20→```bash\\n    21→artifact_dir=$(scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh <input>)\\n    22→```\\n    23→\\n    24→**If given a local path:** Use directly, skip download.\\n    25→\\n    26→## Step 2: Identify Failures\\n    27→\\n    28→For each agent subdirectory in the artifact root:\\n    29→1. Read `report.nocolor.txt` — list failed tests with error messages, file:line references\\n    30→2. Skip agents with zero failures\\n    31→3. Build failure list: `[(test_name, agent, error_line, duration, file:line)]`\\n    32→\\n    33→## Step 3: Analyze Each Failure\\n    34→\\n    35→For each failure, follow the debug-e2e methodology:\\n    36→\\n    37→1. **Read `console.log`** — what did the agent actually do? Full chronological transcript.\\n    38→2. **Read test source at file:line** — what was expected?\\n    39→3. **Read `entire-logs/entire.log`** — any CLI errors, panics, unexpected behavior?\\n    40→4. **Read `git-log.txt` / `git-tree.txt`** — repo state at failure time\\n    41→5. **Read `checkpoint-metadata/`** — corrupt or missing metadata?\\n    42→\\n    43→## Step 4: Classify Each Failure\\n    44→\\n    45→### Strong `real-bug` signals (any one is sufficient):\\n    46→\\n    47→- `entire.log` contains `\\\"level\\\":\\\"ERROR\\\"` or panic/stack traces\\n    48→- Checkpoint metadata structurally corrupt (malformed JSON, missing `checkpoint_id`/`strategy`)\\n    49→- Session state file missing or malformed when expected\\n    50→- Hooks did not fire at all (no `hook invoked` log entries)\\n    51→- Shadow/metadata branch has wrong tree structure\\n    52→- Same test fails across 3+ agents with same non-timeout symptom\\n    53→- Error references CLI code (panic in `cmd/entire/cli/`)\\n    54→- E2E tests do not pass when run locally\\n    55→\\n    56→### Strong `flaky` signals (unless overridden by real-bug):\\n    57→\\n    58→- `signal: killed` (timeout)\\n    59→- `context deadline exceeded` or `WaitForCheckpoint.*exceeded deadline`\\n    60→- Agent asked for confirmation instead of acting\\n    61→- Agent created file at wrong path / wrong name\\n    62→- Agent produced no output\\n    63→- Agent committed when it shouldn't have (or vice versa)\\n    64→- Test pass when run locally\\n    65→- Duration near timeout limit\\n    66→\\n    67→### Ambiguous cases:\\n    68→\\n    69→Read `entire.log` carefully:\\n    70→- If hooks fired correctly and metadata is valid -> lean **flaky**\\n    71→- If hooks fired but produced wrong results -> lean **real-bug**\\n    72→\\n    73→## Step 5: Cross-Agent Correlation\\n    74→\\n    75→Before acting, check correlations:\\n    76→- Same test fails for 3+ agents with similar errors -> override to `real-bug`\\n    77→- Same test passes on second run -> lean `flaky`\\n    78→\\n    79→## Step 6: Take Action\\n    80→\\n    81→### For `flaky` failures: Batched PR\\n    82→\\n    83→1. Create branch `fix/e2e-flaky-<run-id>`\\n    84→2. Apply fixes to ALL flaky test files (one branch, one PR):\\n    85→   - Agent asked for confirmation -> append \\\"Do not ask for confirmation\\\" to prompt\\n    86→   - Agent wrote to wrong path -> be more explicit about paths in prompt\\n    87→   - Agent committed when shouldn't -> add \\\"Do not commit\\\" to prompt\\n    88→   - Checkpoint wait timeout -> increase timeout argument\\n    89→   - Agent timeout (signal: killed) -> increase per-test timeout, simplify prompt\\n    90→3. Run verification:\\n    91→   ```bash\\n    92→   mise run test:e2e:canary   # Must pass\\n    93→   mise run fmt && mise run lint\\n    94→   ```\\n    95→4. If canary fails, investigate and adjust. If unfixable, fall back to issue creation.\\n    96→5. Commit and create PR:\\n    97→   ```bash\\n    98→   gh pr create \\\\\\n    99→     --title \\\"fix(e2e): make flaky tests more resilient (run <run-id>)\\\" \\\\\\n   100→     --body \\\"<structured body with per-test changes, evidence, run link>\\\"\\n   101→   ```\\n   102→\\n   103→### For `real-bug` failures: Issue (with dedup)\\n   104→\\n   105→1. **Search existing issues first:**\\n   106→   ```bash\\n   107→   gh issue list --search \\\"is:open label:e2e <TestName>\\\" --json number,title,url\\n   108→   ```\\n   109→\\n   110→2. **If matching issue exists:** Add a comment with new evidence:\\n   111→   ```bash\\n   112→   gh issue comment <number> --body \\\"<verification details, run link, new evidence>\\\"\\n   113→   ```\\n   114→   Note \\\"Verified still failing in CI run <URL>\\\" plus any new diagnostic details.\\n   115→\\n   116→3. **If no matching issue:** Create new:\\n   117→   ```bash\\n   118→   gh issue create \\\\\\n   119→     --title \\\"E2E: <TestName> fails — <brief symptom>\\\" \\\\\\n   120→     --label \\\"bug,e2e\\\" \\\\\\n   121→     --body \\\"<structured body>\\\"\\n   122→   ```\\n   123→\\n   124→   Issue body includes:\\n   125→   - Test name, agent(s), CI run link, frequency\\n   126→   - Failure summary (expected vs actual)\\n   127→   - Root cause analysis (which CLI component: hooks, session, checkpoint, attribution, strategy)\\n   128→   - Key evidence: `entire.log` excerpts, `console.log` excerpts, git state\\n   129→   - Reproduction steps\\n   130→   - Suspected fix location (file, function, reason)\\n   131→\\n   132→## Step 7: Summary Report\\n   133→\\n   134→Print a summary table:\\n   135→```\\n   136→| Test | Agent(s) | Classification | Action | Link |\\n   137→|------|----------|---------------|--------|------|\\n   138→| TestFoo | claude-code | flaky | PR #123 | url |\\n   139→| TestBar | all agents | real-bug | Issue #456 (existing, commented) | url |\\n   140→| TestBaz | opencode | real-bug | Issue #457 (new) | url |\\n   141→```\\n   142→\\n   143→**Write `triage-summary.json`** in the artifact directory for Slack notifications:\\n   144→\\n   145→```bash\\n   146→cat > \\\"${ARTIFACT_DIR}/triage-summary.json\\\" << 'TEMPLATE'\\n   147→{\\n   148→  \\\"actions\\\": [\\n   149→    {\\n   150→      \\\"test\\\": \\\"TestName\\\",\\n   151→      \\\"agents\\\": [\\\"claude-code\\\", \\\"opencode\\\"],\\n   152→      \\\"classification\\\": \\\"flaky|real-bug\\\",\\n   153→      \\\"action_type\\\": \\\"pr|issue|comment\\\",\\n   154→      \\\"action_description\\\": \\\"PR #123|Issue #456 (new)|Issue #456 (commented)\\\",\\n   155→      \\\"link\\\": \\\"https://github.com/entireio/cli/pull/123\\\"\\n   156→    }\\n   157→  ]\\n   158→}\\n   159→TEMPLATE\\n   160→```\\n   161→\\n   162→Each entry in `actions` corresponds to one row in the summary table. Include all failures that had an action taken. The `link` field must be the full URL to the PR or issue.\\n   163→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"068401d5-b76d-4b1a-90ff-2722f50310af\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T20:36:05.493Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.claude/skills/e2e-triage/SKILL.md\",\"content\":\"---\\nname: e2e-triage\\ndescription: Triage E2E test failures — download CI artifacts, classify flaky vs real bug, create PRs for flaky fixes and GitHub issues for real bugs\\n---\\n\\n# E2E Triage\\n\\nAutomate triage of E2E test failures. Analyze artifacts, classify each failure as **flaky** (agent non-determinism) or **real-bug** (CLI defect), then take action: batched PR for flaky fixes, GitHub issues for real bugs.\\n\\n## Inputs\\n\\nThe user provides one of:\\n- **`latest`** — download artifacts from the most recent failed E2E run on main\\n- **A run ID or URL** — download artifacts from that specific run\\n- **A local path** — use existing artifact directory (skip download)\\n\\n## Step 1: Download Artifacts\\n\\n**If given a run ID, URL, or \\\"latest\\\":**\\n```bash\\nartifact_dir=$(scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh <input>)\\n```\\n\\n**If given a local path:** Use directly, skip download.\\n\\n## Step 2: Identify Failures\\n\\nFor each agent subdirectory in the artifact root:\\n1. Read `report.nocolor.txt` — list failed tests with error messages, file:line references\\n2. Skip agents with zero failures\\n3. Build failure list: `[(test_name, agent, error_line, duration, file:line)]`\\n\\n## Step 3: Analyze Each Failure\\n\\nFor each failure, follow the debug-e2e methodology:\\n\\n1. **Read `console.log`** — what did the agent actually do? Full chronological transcript.\\n2. **Read test source at file:line** — what was expected?\\n3. **Read `entire-logs/entire.log`** — any CLI errors, panics, unexpected behavior?\\n4. **Read `git-log.txt` / `git-tree.txt`** — repo state at failure time\\n5. **Read `checkpoint-metadata/`** — corrupt or missing metadata?\\n\\n## Step 4: Classify Each Failure\\n\\n### Strong `real-bug` signals (any one is sufficient):\\n\\n- `entire.log` contains `\\\"level\\\":\\\"ERROR\\\"` or panic/stack traces\\n- Checkpoint metadata structurally corrupt (malformed JSON, missing `checkpoint_id`/`strategy`)\\n- Session state file missing or malformed when expected\\n- Hooks did not fire at all (no `hook invoked` log entries)\\n- Shadow/metadata branch has wrong tree structure\\n- Same test fails across 3+ agents with same non-timeout symptom\\n- Error references CLI code (panic in `cmd/entire/cli/`)\\n- E2E tests do not pass when run locally\\n\\n### Strong `flaky` signals (unless overridden by real-bug):\\n\\n- `signal: killed` (timeout)\\n- `context deadline exceeded` or `WaitForCheckpoint.*exceeded deadline`\\n- Agent asked for confirmation instead of acting\\n- Agent created file at wrong path / wrong name\\n- Agent produced no output\\n- Agent committed when it shouldn't have (or vice versa)\\n- Test pass when run locally\\n- Duration near timeout limit\\n\\n### Ambiguous cases:\\n\\nRead `entire.log` carefully:\\n- If hooks fired correctly and metadata is valid -> lean **flaky**\\n- If hooks fired but produced wrong results -> lean **real-bug**\\n\\n## Step 5: Cross-Agent Correlation\\n\\nBefore acting, check correlations:\\n- Same test fails for 3+ agents with similar errors -> override to `real-bug`\\n- Same test passes on second run -> lean `flaky`\\n\\n## Step 6: Take Action\\n\\n### For `flaky` failures: Batched PR\\n\\n1. Create branch `fix/e2e-flaky-<run-id>`\\n2. Apply fixes to ALL flaky test files (one branch, one PR):\\n   - Agent asked for confirmation -> append \\\"Do not ask for confirmation\\\" to prompt\\n   - Agent wrote to wrong path -> be more explicit about paths in prompt\\n   - Agent committed when shouldn't -> add \\\"Do not commit\\\" to prompt\\n   - Checkpoint wait timeout -> increase timeout argument\\n   - Agent timeout (signal: killed) -> increase per-test timeout, simplify prompt\\n3. Run verification:\\n   ```bash\\n   mise run test:e2e:canary   # Must pass\\n   mise run fmt && mise run lint\\n   ```\\n4. If canary fails, investigate and adjust. If unfixable, fall back to issue creation.\\n5. Commit and create PR:\\n   ```bash\\n   gh pr create \\\\\\n     --title \\\"fix(e2e): make flaky tests more resilient (run <run-id>)\\\" \\\\\\n     --body \\\"<structured body with per-test changes, evidence, run link>\\\"\\n   ```\\n\\n### For `real-bug` failures: Issue (with dedup)\\n\\n1. **Search existing issues first:**\\n   ```bash\\n   gh issue list --search \\\"is:open label:e2e <TestName>\\\" --json number,title,url\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **If matching issue exists:** Add a comment with new evidence:\\n   ```bash\\n   gh issue comment <number> --body \\\"<verification details, run link, new evidence>\\\"\\n   ```\\n   Note \\\"Verified still failing in CI run <URL>\\\" plus any new diagnostic details.\\n\\n3. **If no matching issue:** Create new:\\n   ```bash\\n   gh issue create \\\\\\n     --title \\\"E2E: <TestName> fails — <brief symptom>\\\" \\\\\\n     --label \\\"bug,e2e\\\" \\\\\\n     --body \\\"<structured body>\\\"\\n   ```\\n\\n   Issue body includes:\\n   - Test name, agent(s), CI run link, frequency\\n   - Failure summary (expected vs actual)\\n   - Root cause analysis (which CLI component: hooks, session, checkpoint, attribution, strategy)\\n   - Key evidence: `entire.log` excerpts, `console.log` excerpts, git state\\n   - Reproduction steps\\n   - Suspected fix location (file, function, reason)\\n\\n## Step 7: Summary Report\\n\\nPrint a summary table:\\n```\\n| Test | Agent(s) | Classification | Action | Link |\\n|------|----------|---------------|--------|------|\\n| TestFoo | claude-code | flaky | PR #123 | url |\\n| TestBar | all agents | real-bug | Issue #456 (existing, commented) | url |\\n| TestBaz | opencode | real-bug | Issue #457 (new) | url |\\n```\\n\\n**Write `triage-summary.json`** in the artifact directory for Slack notifications:\\n\\n```bash\\ncat > \\\"${ARTIFACT_DIR}/triage-summary.json\\\" << 'TEMPLATE'\\n{\\n  \\\"actions\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"test\\\": \\\"TestName\\\",\\n      \\\"agents\\\": [\\\"claude-code\\\", \\\"opencode\\\"],\\n      \\\"classification\\\": \\\"flaky|real-bug\\\",\\n      \\\"action_type\\\": \\\"pr|issue|comment\\\",\\n      \\\"action_description\\\": \\\"PR #123|Issue #456 (new)|Issue #456 (commented)\\\",\\n      \\\"link\\\": \\\"https://github.com/entireio/cli/pull/123\\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\\nTEMPLATE\\n```\\n\\nEach entry in `actions` corresponds to one row in the summary table. Include all failures that had an action taken. The `link` field must be the full URL to the PR or issue.\\n\",\"numLines\":163,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":163}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"13b266f8-da67-4cd9-924f-3bf9c7d79826\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"068401d5-b76d-4b1a-90ff-2722f50310af\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"8f15321d-2333-415f-a295-a31e4d8776e8\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/e2e-triage\",\"slug\":\"agile-twirling-flask\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01TTY6EUg5c94weVxzFy2KGK\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01QGTWhjPNtL2H1aM8AMiemx\",\"name\":\"Glob\",\"input\":{\"pattern\":\".github/workflows/*e2e*\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4470,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":27856,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":4470},\"output_tokens\":26,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYnU5XckhMUMNCM3i4ZzC\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"755487d4-c03a-4cbc-9562-1e36cedf3d7d\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T20:36:05.820Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"755487d4-c03a-4cbc-9562-1e36cedf3d7d\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"8f15321d-2333-415f-a295-a31e4d8776e8\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/e2e-triage\",\"slug\":\"agile-twirling-flask\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01TTY6EUg5c94weVxzFy2KGK\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01J5YUwB1dnNMLMYp1aekS9y\",\"name\":\"Glob\",\"input\":{\"pattern\":\".claude/