cks until the run completes and prints the result. This is simpler than polling `gh run list`. However, `gh run watch` requires a TTY in some versions. The safer approach for CI (headless) is:\\n   ```bash\\n   # Get the run ID right after dispatch\\n   gh run list -w e2e-isolated.yml -L 1 --json databaseId -q '.[0].databaseId'\\n   \\n   # Then poll\\n   gh run view <run_id> --json status,conclusion\\n   ```\\n\\n5. **NEW: Download artifacts from the re-run**:\\n   ```bash\\n   gh run download <run_id> --dir <rerun_artifact_dir>\\n   ```\\n\\n6. Repeat for a second re-run of each failing test.\\n\\n7. The skill then has: original failure artifacts + 2 re-run results per test. This feeds into classification.\\n\\n**Sequencing concern**: If there are many failing tests across multiple agents, triggering all re-runs in parallel would be more efficient. The skill should dispatch all `gh workflow run` calls first, collect the run IDs, then wait for all to complete. However, `e2e-isolated.yml` does not have a concurrency group, so multiple runs can proceed in parallel. If this is a concern, the skill should note dispatching them serially or in small batches.\\n\\nActually, looking at the `e2e-isolated.yml` workflow, it has no concurrency group, so multiple isolated runs can execute in parallel on different runners. The skill should:\\n- Dispatch all re-runs (2 per failing test+agent pair) upfront\\n- Collect all run IDs\\n- Wait for all to complete\\n- Download all artifacts\\n\\n#### Step 2: Unified Failure Analysis with Re-run Data\\n\\nAfter re-runs complete (either locally or via CI), build an enriched failure table:\\n\\n```\\n[(test_name, agent, original_result, rerun_1_result, rerun_2_result, artifacts...)]\\n```\\n\\nClassification signals from re-runs:\\n- **All 3 runs fail with same error** --> strong `real-bug` signal\\n- **Original fails, both re-runs pass** --> strong `flaky` signal  \\n- **Mixed results (1 fail, 1 pass in re-runs)** --> `flaky` (non-deterministic)\\n- **Original fails, re-runs fail with different error** --> needs manual analysis\\n\\nThis replaces the weaker signals in the current Step 5 (\\\"Same test passes on second run -> lean flaky\\\") with concrete data.\\n\\n#### Steps 3-7: Mostly Unchanged\\n\\nThe analysis (Step 3), classification (Step 4), cross-agent correlation (Step 5), action (Step 6), and summary (Step 7) sections remain largely the same. The key changes:\\n\\n- Step 4 gains a new strong signal: \\\"Test passes on re-run(s) -> `flaky`\\\" and \\\"Test fails consistently across re-runs -> `real-bug`\\\"\\n- Step 5 cross-agent correlation can use re-run data: if a test fails for one agent but passes on re-run, while failing consistently for another agent, the per-agent classification can differ\\n- Step 7 summary table gains a \\\"Re-run results\\\" column\\n\\n#### Changes to e2e-triage.yml Workflow\\n\\nThe workflow itself needs minor updates:\\n\\n1. **Add `actions: write` permission** -- needed to trigger `gh workflow run e2e-isolated.yml`\\n2. **Increase timeout** -- from 30 minutes to maybe 60 minutes, since re-runs via `e2e-isolated.yml` take ~20 minutes each\\n3. **Update the Claude prompt** to mention the re-run capability\\n4. **Add `Bash(gh workflow run *)` to allowedTools** -- already covered by `Bash(gh *)`\\n\\n#### Changes to e2e-isolated.yml Workflow\\n\\nNo changes needed. It already accepts `agent` and `test` inputs via `workflow_dispatch` and uploads artifacts.\\n\\n### Potential Challenges\\n\\n1. **Run ID discovery after `gh workflow run`**: `gh workflow run` does not return the run ID. The skill must use `gh run list -w e2e-isolated.yml` immediately after dispatch to find it. There is a small race window. The skill should document a pattern like:\\n   ```bash\\n   # Record timestamp before dispatch\\n   gh workflow run e2e-isolated.yml -f agent=claude-code -f test=TestFoo\\n   sleep 5\\n   # Find the most recent run for this workflow\\n   gh run list -w e2e-isolated.yml -L 1 --json databaseId -q '.[0].databaseId'\\n   ```\\n   For multiple concurrent dispatches, the skill needs to be more careful -- dispatch one at a time with a small delay, recording each run ID.\\n\\n2. **CI timeout**: If there are 5 failing tests each needing 2 re-runs, that is 10 isolated workflow runs. Each takes ~20 minutes. Even in parallel, this could take 20-40 minutes. The triage workflow timeout should be 60 minutes minimum.\\n\\n3. **Local mode cost**: Running real E2E tests locally costs API tokens. The skill should warn the user and confirm before proceeding (unless given explicit test names).\\n\\n4. **Artifact structure differences**: Local `mise run test:e2e` artifacts have a flat structure (`e2e/artifacts/<timestamp>/`), while CI artifacts downloaded via `gh run download` have a different structure. The skill already handles this via `download-e2e-artifacts.sh`, but re-run artifacts from `e2e-isolated.yml` will be in the `e2e-isolated-<agent>-<test>` artifact name format.\\n\\n### Critical Files for Implementation\\n\\n### Critical Files for Implementation\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.claude/skills/e2e-triage/SKILL.md` - The primary file to rewrite with dual-mode (local + CI) triage instructions, re-run logic, and updated classification signals\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.github/workflows/e2e-triage.yml` - Needs permission update (`actions: write`), timeout increase (30m to 60m), and updated Claude prompt mentioning re-run capability\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.github/workflows/e2e-isolated.yml` - Reference file (no changes needed) -- the `workflow_dispatch` target for CI re-runs, must understand its inputs (`agent`, `test`) and artifact naming\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/mise-tasks/test/e2e/_default` - Reference file (no changes needed) -- the local test runner command, must understand its interface (`--agent`, filter arg, artifact output)\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.claude/skills/de